Header.Info: Performance Monitoring Events for 12th and 13th Generation Intel(R) Core(TM) Processor - V1.36

Events.BriefDescription: Counts the total number of instructions retired. (Fixed event)
Events.PublicDescription: Counts the total number of instructions that retired. For instructions that consist of multiple uops, this event counts the retirement of the last uop of the instruction. This event continues counting during hardware interrupts, traps, and inside interrupt handlers. This event uses fixed counter 0.

Events.BriefDescription: Counts the number of unhalted core clock cycles. (Fixed event)
Events.PublicDescription: Counts the number of core cycles while the core is not in a halt state. The core enters the halt state when it is running the HLT instruction. The core frequency may change from time to time. For this reason this event may have a changing ratio with regards to time. This event uses fixed counter 1.

Events.BriefDescription: Fixed Counter: Counts the number of unhalted core clock cycles. [This event is alias to CPU_CLK_UNHALTED.CORE]
Events.PublicDescription: Counts the number of core cycles while the core is not in a halt state.  The core enters the halt state when it is running the HLT instruction. The core frequency may change from time to time. For this reason this event may have a changing ratio with regards to time.  This event uses fixed counter 1.

Events.BriefDescription: Counts the number of unhalted reference clock cycles at TSC frequency. (Fixed event)
Events.PublicDescription: Counts the number of reference cycles that the core is not in a halt state. The core enters the halt state when it is running the HLT instruction. This event is not affected by core frequency changes and increments at a fixed frequency that is also used for the Time Stamp Counter (TSC). This event uses fixed counter 2.

Events.BriefDescription: Counts the number of retired loads that are blocked because its address exactly matches an older store whose data is not ready.
Events.PublicDescription: Counts the number of retired loads that are blocked because its address exactly matches an older store whose data is not ready.

Events.BriefDescription: This event is deprecated. Refer to new event LD_BLOCKS.ADDRESS_ALIAS
Events.PublicDescription: This event is deprecated. Refer to new event LD_BLOCKS.ADDRESS_ALIAS

Events.BriefDescription: Counts the number of retired loads that are blocked because it initially appears to be store forward blocked, but subsequently is shown not to be blocked based on 4K alias check.
Events.PublicDescription: Counts the number of retired loads that are blocked because it initially appears to be store forward blocked, but subsequently is shown not to be blocked based on 4K alias check.

Events.BriefDescription: Counts the number of cycles that uops are blocked due to a store buffer full condition.
Events.PublicDescription: Counts the number of cycles that uops are blocked due to a store buffer full condition.

Events.BriefDescription: Counts the number of cycles that uops are blocked due to a load buffer full condition.
Events.PublicDescription: Counts the number of cycles that uops are blocked due to a load buffer full condition.

Events.BriefDescription: Counts the number of cycles that uops are blocked due to an RSV full condition.
Events.PublicDescription: Counts the number of cycles that uops are blocked due to an RSV full condition.

Events.BriefDescription: Counts the number of cycles that uops are blocked for any of the following reasons:  load buffer, store buffer or RSV full.
Events.PublicDescription: Counts the number of cycles that uops are blocked for any of the following reasons:  load buffer, store buffer or RSV full.

Events.BriefDescription: Counts the number of cycles that the head (oldest load) of the load buffer and retirement are both stalled due to a DL1 miss.
Events.PublicDescription: Counts the number of cycles that the head (oldest load) of the load buffer and retirement are both stalled due to a DL1 miss.

Events.BriefDescription: Counts the number of cycles that the head (oldest load) of the load buffer and retirement are both stalled due to a store address match.
Events.PublicDescription: Counts the number of cycles that the head (oldest load) of the load buffer and retirement are both stalled due to a store address match.

Events.BriefDescription: Counts the number of cycles that the head (oldest load) of the load buffer and retirement are both stalled due to a DTLB miss.
Events.PublicDescription: Counts the number of cycles that the head (oldest load) of the load buffer and retirement are both stalled due to a DTLB miss.

Events.BriefDescription: Counts the number of cycles that the head (oldest load) of the load buffer and retirement are both stalled due to a pagewalk.
Events.PublicDescription: Counts the number of cycles that the head (oldest load) of the load buffer and retirement are both stalled due to a pagewalk.

Events.BriefDescription: Counts the number of cycles that the head (oldest load) of the load buffer and retirement are both stalled due to other block cases.
Events.PublicDescription: Counts the number of cycles that the head (oldest load) of the load buffer and retirement are both stalled due to other block cases such as pipeline conflicts, fences, etc.

Events.BriefDescription: Counts the number of cycles that the head (oldest load) of the load buffer is stalled due to a core bound stall including a store address match, a DTLB miss or a page walk that detains the load from retiring.
Events.PublicDescription: Counts the number of cycles that the head (oldest load) of the load buffer is stalled due to a core bound stall including a store address match, a DTLB miss or a page walk that detains the load from retiring.

Events.BriefDescription: Counts the number of cycles that the head (oldest load) of the load buffer is stalled due to any number of reasons, including an L1 miss, WCB full, pagewalk, store address block or store data block, on a load that retires.
Events.PublicDescription: Counts the number of cycles that the head (oldest load) of the load buffer is stalled due to any number of reasons, including an L1 miss, WCB full, pagewalk, store address block or store data block, on a load that retires.

Events.BriefDescription: Counts the number of page walks completed due to load DTLB misses to any page size.
Events.PublicDescription: Counts the number of page walks completed due to loads (including SW prefetches) whose address translations missed in all Translation Lookaside Buffer (TLB) levels and were mapped to any page size. Includes page walks that page fault.

Events.BriefDescription: Counts the number of uops issued by the front end every cycle.
Events.PublicDescription: Counts the number of uops issued by the front end every cycle. When 4-uops are requested and only 2-uops are delivered, the event counts 2.  Uops_issued correlates to the number of ROB entries.  If uop takes 2 ROB slots it counts as 2 uops_issued.

Events.BriefDescription: Counts the total number of L2 Cache accesses. Counts on a per core basis.
Events.PublicDescription: Counts the total number of L2 Cache Accesses, includes hits, misses, rejects  front door requests for CRd/DRd/RFO/ItoM/L2 Prefetches only.  Counts on a per core basis.

Events.BriefDescription: Counts the number of L2 Cache accesses that resulted in a miss. Counts on a per core basis.
Events.PublicDescription: Counts the number of L2 Cache accesses that resulted in a miss from a front door request only (does not include rejects or recycles). Counts on a per core basis.

Events.BriefDescription: Counts the number of L2 Cache accesses that resulted in a hit. Counts on a per core basis.
Events.PublicDescription: Counts the number of L2 Cache accesses that resulted in a hit from a front door request only (does not include rejects or recycles), Counts on a per core basis.

Events.BriefDescription: Counts the number of cacheable memory requests that miss in the LLC. Counts on a per core basis.
Events.PublicDescription: Counts the number of cacheable memory requests that miss in the Last Level Cache (LLC). Requests include demand loads, reads for ownership (RFO), instruction fetches and L1 HW prefetches. If the core has access to an L3 cache, the LLC is the L3 cache, otherwise it is the L2 cache. Counts on a per core basis.

Events.BriefDescription: Counts the number of cacheable memory requests that access the LLC. Counts on a per core basis.
Events.PublicDescription: Counts the number of cacheable memory requests that access the Last Level Cache (LLC). Requests include demand loads, reads for ownership (RFO), instruction fetches and L1 HW prefetches. If the core has access to an L3 cache, the LLC is the L3 cache, otherwise it is the L2 cache. Counts on a per core basis.

Events.BriefDescription: Counts the number of cycles the core is stalled due to a demand load which hit in the L2 cache.
Events.PublicDescription: Counts the number of cycles the core is stalled due to a demand load which hit in the L2 cache.

Events.BriefDescription: Counts the number of cycles the core is stalled due to a demand load which hit in the LLC or other core with HITE/F/M.
Events.PublicDescription: Counts the number of cycles the core is stalled due to a demand load which hit in the Last Level Cache (LLC) or other core with HITE/F/M.

Events.BriefDescription: Counts the number of cycles the core is stalled due to a demand load miss which hit in DRAM or MMIO (Non-DRAM).
Events.PublicDescription: Counts the number of cycles the core is stalled due to a demand load miss which hit in DRAM or MMIO (Non-DRAM).

Events.BriefDescription: Counts the number of cycles the core is stalled due to a demand load miss which hit in the L2, LLC, DRAM or MMIO (Non-DRAM).
Events.PublicDescription: Counts the number of cycles the core is stalled due to a demand load miss which hit in the L2, LLC, DRAM or MMIO (Non-DRAM).

Events.BriefDescription: Counts the number of cycles the core is stalled due to an instruction cache or TLB miss which hit in the L2 cache.
Events.PublicDescription: Counts the number of cycles the core is stalled due to an instruction cache or Translation Lookaside Buffer (TLB) miss which hit in the L2 cache.

Events.BriefDescription: Counts the number of cycles the core is stalled due to an instruction cache or TLB miss which hit in the LLC or other core with HITE/F/M.
Events.PublicDescription: Counts the number of cycles the core is stalled due to an instruction cache or Translation Lookaside Buffer (TLB) miss which hit in the Last Level Cache (LLC) or other core with HITE/F/M.

Events.BriefDescription: Counts the number of cycles the core is stalled due to an instruction cache or TLB miss which hit in DRAM or MMIO (Non-DRAM).
Events.PublicDescription: Counts the number of cycles the core is stalled due to an instruction cache or translation lookaside buffer (TLB) miss which hit in DRAM or MMIO (non-DRAM).

Events.BriefDescription: Counts the number of cycles the core is stalled due to an instruction cache or TLB miss which hit in the L2, LLC, DRAM or MMIO (Non-DRAM).
Events.PublicDescription: Counts the number of cycles the core is stalled due to an instruction cache or translation lookaside buffer (TLB) miss which hit in the L2, LLC, DRAM or MMIO (Non-DRAM).

Events.BriefDescription: Counts the number of unhalted core clock cycles.
Events.PublicDescription: Counts the number of core cycles while the core is not in a halt state. The core enters the halt state when it is running the HLT instruction. The core frequency may change from time to time. For this reason this event may have a changing ratio with regards to time. This event uses a programmable general purpose performance counter.

Events.BriefDescription: Counts the number of unhalted core clock cycles. [This event is alias to CPU_CLK_UNHALTED.CORE_P]
Events.PublicDescription: Counts the number of core cycles while the core is not in a halt state.  The core enters the halt state when it is running the HLT instruction. The core frequency may change from time to time. For this reason this event may have a changing ratio with regards to time. This event uses a programmable general purpose performance counter.

Events.BriefDescription: Counts the number of unhalted reference clock cycles at TSC frequency.
Events.PublicDescription: Counts the number of reference cycles that the core is not in a halt state. The core enters the halt state when it is running the HLT instruction. This event is not affected by core frequency changes and increments at a fixed frequency that is also used for the Time Stamp Counter (TSC). This event uses a programmable general purpose performance counter.

Events.BriefDescription: This event is deprecated. Refer to new event CPU_CLK_UNHALTED.REF_TSC_P
Events.PublicDescription: This event is deprecated. Refer to new event CPU_CLK_UNHALTED.REF_TSC_P

Events.BriefDescription: Counts the number of page walks completed due to store DTLB misses to any page size.
Events.PublicDescription: Counts the number of page walks completed due to stores whose address translations missed in all Translation Lookaside Buffer (TLB) levels and were mapped to any page size.  Includes page walks that page fault.

Events.BriefDescription: Counts the total number of issue slots every cycle that were not consumed by the backend due to frontend stalls.
Events.PublicDescription: Counts the total number of issue slots every cycle that were not consumed by the backend due to frontend stalls.

Events.BriefDescription: Counts the number of issue slots every cycle that were not delivered by the frontend due to the microcode sequencer (MS).
Events.PublicDescription: Counts the number of issue slots every cycle that were not delivered by the frontend due to the microcode sequencer (MS).

Events.BriefDescription: Counts the number of issue slots every cycle that were not delivered by the frontend due to BACLEARS.
Events.PublicDescription: Counts the number of issue slots every cycle that were not delivered by the frontend due to BACLEARS, which occurs when the Branch Target Buffer (BTB) prediction or lack thereof, was corrected by a later branch predictor in the frontend. Includes BACLEARS due to all branch types including conditional and unconditional jumps, returns, and indirect branches.

Events.BriefDescription: Counts the number of issue slots every cycle that were not delivered by the frontend due to wrong predecodes.
Events.PublicDescription: Counts the number of issue slots every cycle that were not delivered by the frontend due to wrong predecodes.

Events.BriefDescription: Counts the number of issue slots every cycle that were not delivered by the frontend due to decode stalls.
Events.PublicDescription: Counts the number of issue slots every cycle that were not delivered by the frontend due to decode stalls.

Events.BriefDescription: Counts the number of issue slots every cycle that were not delivered by the frontend due to ITLB misses.
Events.PublicDescription: Counts the number of issue slots every cycle that were not delivered by the frontend due to Instruction Table Lookaside Buffer (ITLB) misses.

Events.BriefDescription: Counts the number of issue slots every cycle that were not delivered by the frontend due to instruction cache misses.
Events.PublicDescription: Counts the number of issue slots every cycle that were not delivered by the frontend due to instruction cache misses.

Events.BriefDescription: Counts the number of issue slots every cycle that were not delivered by the frontend due to BTCLEARS.
Events.PublicDescription: Counts the number of issue slots every cycle that were not delivered by the frontend due to BTCLEARS, which occurs when the Branch Target Buffer (BTB) predicts a taken branch.

Events.BriefDescription: Counts the number of issue slots every cycle that were not delivered by the frontend due to a latency related stalls including BACLEARs, BTCLEARs, ITLB misses, and ICache misses.
Events.PublicDescription: Counts the number of issue slots every cycle that were not delivered by the frontend due to a latency related stalls including BACLEARs, BTCLEARs, ITLB misses, and ICache misses.

Events.BriefDescription: Counts the number of issue slots every cycle that were not delivered by the frontend due to other common frontend stalls not categorized.
Events.PublicDescription: Counts the number of issue slots every cycle that were not delivered by the frontend due to other common frontend stalls not categorized.

Events.BriefDescription: Counts the number of issue slots every cycle that were not delivered by the frontend due to frontend bandwidth restrictions due to decode, predecode, cisc, and other limitations.
Events.PublicDescription: Counts the number of issue slots every cycle that were not delivered by the frontend due to frontend bandwidth restrictions due to decode, predecode, cisc, and other limitations.

Events.BriefDescription: Counts the total number of issue slots that were not consumed by the backend because allocation is stalled due to a mispredicted jump or a machine clear.
Events.PublicDescription: Counts the total number of issue slots that were not consumed by the backend because allocation is stalled due to a mispredicted jump or a machine clear. Only issue slots wasted due to fast nukes such as memory ordering nukes are counted. Other nukes are not accounted for. Counts all issue slots blocked during this recovery window including relevant microcode flows and while uops are not yet available in the instruction queue (IQ) even if an FE_bound event occurs during this period. Also includes the issue slots that were consumed by the backend but were thrown away because they were younger than the mispredict or machine clear.

Events.BriefDescription: Counts the number of issue slots every cycle that were not consumed by the backend due to a machine clear (nuke).
Events.PublicDescription: Counts the number of issue slots every cycle that were not consumed by the backend due to a machine clear (nuke).

Events.BriefDescription: Counts the number of issue slots every cycle that were not consumed by the backend due to fast nukes such as memory ordering and memory disambiguation machine clears.
Events.PublicDescription: Counts the number of issue slots every cycle that were not consumed by the backend due to fast nukes such as memory ordering and memory disambiguation machine clears.

Events.BriefDescription: Counts the total number of issue slots that were not consumed by the backend because allocation is stalled due to a machine clear (nuke) of any kind including memory ordering and memory disambiguation.
Events.PublicDescription: Counts the total number of issue slots that were not consumed by the backend because allocation is stalled due to a machine clear (nuke) of any kind including memory ordering and memory disambiguation.

Events.BriefDescription: Counts the number of issue slots every cycle that were not consumed by the backend due to branch mispredicts.
Events.PublicDescription: Counts the number of issue slots every cycle that were not consumed by the backend due to branch mispredicts.

Events.BriefDescription: Counts the total number of issue slots every cycle that were not consumed by the backend due to backend stalls.
Events.PublicDescription: Counts the total number of issue slots every cycle that were not consumed by the backend due to backend stalls.

Events.BriefDescription: Counts the number of issue slots every cycle that were not consumed by the backend due to certain allocation restrictions.
Events.PublicDescription: Counts the number of issue slots every cycle that were not consumed by the backend due to certain allocation restrictions.

Events.BriefDescription: Counts the number of issue slots every cycle that were not consumed by the backend due to memory reservation stalls in which a scheduler is not able to accept uops.
Events.PublicDescription: Counts the number of issue slots every cycle that were not consumed by the backend due to memory reservation stalls in which a scheduler is not able to accept uops.

Events.BriefDescription: Counts the number of issue slots every cycle that were not consumed by the backend due to IEC or FPC RAT stalls, which can be due to FIQ or IEC reservation stalls in which the integer, floating point or SIMD scheduler is not able to accept uops.
Events.PublicDescription: Counts the number of issue slots every cycle that were not consumed by the backend due to IEC or FPC RAT stalls, which can be due to FIQ or IEC reservation stalls in which the integer, floating point or SIMD scheduler is not able to accept uops.

Events.BriefDescription: Counts the number of issue slots every cycle that were not consumed by the backend due to scoreboards from the instruction queue (IQ), jump execution unit (JEU), or microcode sequencer (MS).
Events.PublicDescription: Counts the number of issue slots every cycle that were not consumed by the backend due to scoreboards from the instruction queue (IQ), jump execution unit (JEU), or microcode sequencer (MS).

Events.BriefDescription: Counts the number of issue slots every cycle that were not consumed by the backend due to the physical register file unable to accept an entry (marble stalls).
Events.PublicDescription: Counts the number of issue slots every cycle that were not consumed by the backend due to the physical register file unable to accept an entry (marble stalls).

Events.BriefDescription: Counts the number of issue slots every cycle that were not consumed by the backend due to the reorder buffer being full (ROB stalls).
Events.PublicDescription: Counts the number of issue slots every cycle that were not consumed by the backend due to the reorder buffer being full (ROB stalls).

Events.BriefDescription: Counts the number of issue slots not consumed by the backend due to a micro-sequencer (MS) scoreboard, which stalls the front-end from issuing from the UROM until a specified older uop retires.
Events.PublicDescription: Counts the number of issue slots not consumed by the backend due to a micro-sequencer (MS) scoreboard, which stalls the front-end from issuing from the UROM until a specified older uop retires. The most commonly executed instruction with an MS scoreboard is PAUSE.

Events.BriefDescription: Counts the number of issue slots in a UMWAIT or TPAUSE instruction where no uop issues due to the instruction putting the CPU into the C0.1 activity state. For Tremont, UMWAIT and TPAUSE will only put the CPU into C0.1 activity state (not C0.2 activity state)
Events.PublicDescription: Counts the number of issue slots in a UMWAIT or TPAUSE instruction where no uop issues due to the instruction putting the CPU into the C0.1 activity state. For Tremont, UMWAIT and TPAUSE will only put the CPU into C0.1 activity state (not C0.2 activity state)

Events.BriefDescription: Counts the number of instruction cache misses.
Events.PublicDescription: Counts the number of missed requests to the instruction cache.  The event only counts new cache line accesses, so that multiple back to back fetches to the exact same cache line and byte chunk count as one.  Specifically, the event counts when accesses from sequential code crosses the cache line boundary, or when a branch target is moved to a new line or to a non-sequential byte chunk of the same line.

Events.BriefDescription: Counts the number of requests to the instruction cache for one or more bytes of a cache line.
Events.PublicDescription: Counts the total number of requests to the instruction cache.  The event only counts new cache line accesses, so that multiple back to back fetches to the exact same cache line or byte chunk count as one.  Specifically, the event counts when accesses from sequential code crosses the cache line boundary, or when a branch target is moved to a new line or to a non-sequential byte chunk of the same line.

Events.BriefDescription: Counts the number of page walks initiated by a instruction fetch that missed the first and second level TLBs.
Events.PublicDescription: Counts the number of page walks initiated by a instruction fetch that missed the first and second level TLBs.

Events.BriefDescription: Counts the number of page walks completed due to instruction fetch misses to any page size.
Events.PublicDescription: Counts the number of page walks completed due to instruction fetches whose address translations missed in all Translation Lookaside Buffer (TLB) levels and were mapped to any page size.  Includes page walks that page fault.

Events.BriefDescription: Counts the number of page walks due to an instruction fetch that miss the PDE (Page Directory Entry) cache.
Events.PublicDescription: Counts the number of page walks due to an instruction fetch that miss the PDE (Page Directory Entry) cache.

Events.BriefDescription: Counts demand data reads that have any type of response.
Events.PublicDescription: Counts demand data reads that have any type of response.

Events.BriefDescription: Counts demand data reads that were supplied by DRAM.
Events.PublicDescription: Counts demand data reads that were supplied by DRAM.

Events.BriefDescription: Counts demand data reads that were not supplied by the L3 cache.
Events.PublicDescription: Counts demand data reads that were not supplied by the L3 cache.

Events.BriefDescription: Counts demand reads for ownership (RFO) and software prefetches for exclusive ownership (PREFETCHW) that have any type of response.
Events.PublicDescription: Counts demand reads for ownership (RFO) and software prefetches for exclusive ownership (PREFETCHW) that have any type of response.

Events.BriefDescription: Counts demand reads for ownership (RFO) and software prefetches for exclusive ownership (PREFETCHW) that were supplied by DRAM.
Events.PublicDescription: Counts demand reads for ownership (RFO) and software prefetches for exclusive ownership (PREFETCHW) that were supplied by DRAM.

Events.BriefDescription: Counts demand reads for ownership (RFO) and software prefetches for exclusive ownership (PREFETCHW) that were not supplied by the L3 cache.
Events.PublicDescription: Counts demand reads for ownership (RFO) and software prefetches for exclusive ownership (PREFETCHW) that were not supplied by the L3 cache.

Events.BriefDescription: Counts demand instruction fetches and L1 instruction cache prefetches that have any type of response.
Events.PublicDescription: Counts demand instruction fetches and L1 instruction cache prefetches that have any type of response.

Events.BriefDescription: Counts demand instruction fetches and L1 instruction cache prefetches that were supplied by DRAM.
Events.PublicDescription: Counts demand instruction fetches and L1 instruction cache prefetches that were supplied by DRAM.

Events.BriefDescription: Counts demand instruction fetches and L1 instruction cache prefetches that were not supplied by the L3 cache.
Events.PublicDescription: Counts demand instruction fetches and L1 instruction cache prefetches that were not supplied by the L3 cache.

Events.BriefDescription: Counts modified writebacks from L1 cache and L2 cache that have any type of response.
Events.PublicDescription: Counts modified writebacks from L1 cache and L2 cache that have any type of response.

Events.BriefDescription: Counts streaming stores that have any type of response.
Events.PublicDescription: Counts streaming stores that have any type of response.

Events.BriefDescription: Counts L1 data cache software prefetches which include T0/T1/T2 and NTA (except PREFETCHW) that have any type of response.
Events.PublicDescription: Counts L1 data cache software prefetches which include T0/T1/T2 and NTA (except PREFETCHW) that have any type of response.

Events.BriefDescription: Counts L1 data cache software prefetches which include T0/T1/T2 and NTA (except PREFETCHW) that were supplied by DRAM.
Events.PublicDescription: Counts L1 data cache software prefetches which include T0/T1/T2 and NTA (except PREFETCHW) that were supplied by DRAM.

Events.BriefDescription: Counts L1 data cache software prefetches which include T0/T1/T2 and NTA (except PREFETCHW) that were not supplied by the L3 cache.
Events.PublicDescription: Counts L1 data cache software prefetches which include T0/T1/T2 and NTA (except PREFETCHW) that were not supplied by the L3 cache.

Events.BriefDescription: Counts streaming stores which modify only part of a 64 byte cacheline that have any type of response.
Events.PublicDescription: Counts streaming stores which modify only part of a 64 byte cacheline that have any type of response.

Events.BriefDescription: Counts streaming stores which modify a full 64 byte cacheline that have any type of response.
Events.PublicDescription: Counts streaming stores which modify a full 64 byte cacheline that have any type of response.

Events.BriefDescription: Counts demand data reads that were supplied by the L3 cache where a snoop was sent, the snoop hit, but no data was forwarded.
Events.PublicDescription: Counts demand data reads that were supplied by the L3 cache where a snoop was sent, the snoop hit, but no data was forwarded.

Events.BriefDescription: Counts demand data reads that were supplied by the L3 cache where a snoop was sent, the snoop hit, and non-modified data was forwarded.
Events.PublicDescription: Counts demand data reads that were supplied by the L3 cache where a snoop was sent, the snoop hit, and non-modified data was forwarded.

Events.BriefDescription: Counts demand data reads that were supplied by the L3 cache where a snoop was sent, the snoop hit, and modified data was forwarded.
Events.PublicDescription: Counts demand data reads that were supplied by the L3 cache where a snoop was sent, the snoop hit, and modified data was forwarded.

Events.BriefDescription: Counts demand reads for ownership (RFO) and software prefetches for exclusive ownership (PREFETCHW) that were supplied by the L3 cache where a snoop was sent, the snoop hit, but no data was forwarded.
Events.PublicDescription: Counts demand reads for ownership (RFO) and software prefetches for exclusive ownership (PREFETCHW) that were supplied by the L3 cache where a snoop was sent, the snoop hit, but no data was forwarded.

Events.BriefDescription: Counts demand reads for ownership (RFO) and software prefetches for exclusive ownership (PREFETCHW) that were supplied by the L3 cache where a snoop was sent, the snoop hit, and non-modified data was forwarded.
Events.PublicDescription: Counts demand reads for ownership (RFO) and software prefetches for exclusive ownership (PREFETCHW) that were supplied by the L3 cache where a snoop was sent, the snoop hit, and non-modified data was forwarded.

Events.BriefDescription: Counts demand reads for ownership (RFO) and software prefetches for exclusive ownership (PREFETCHW) that were supplied by the L3 cache where a snoop was sent, the snoop hit, and modified data was forwarded.
Events.PublicDescription: Counts demand reads for ownership (RFO) and software prefetches for exclusive ownership (PREFETCHW) that were supplied by the L3 cache where a snoop was sent, the snoop hit, and modified data was forwarded.

Events.BriefDescription: Counts demand instruction fetches and L1 instruction cache prefetches that were supplied by the L3 cache where a snoop was sent, the snoop hit, but no data was forwarded.
Events.PublicDescription: Counts demand instruction fetches and L1 instruction cache prefetches that were supplied by the L3 cache where a snoop was sent, the snoop hit, but no data was forwarded.

Events.BriefDescription: Counts demand instruction fetches and L1 instruction cache prefetches that were supplied by the L3 cache where a snoop was sent, the snoop hit, and non-modified data was forwarded.
Events.PublicDescription: Counts demand instruction fetches and L1 instruction cache prefetches that were supplied by the L3 cache where a snoop was sent, the snoop hit, and non-modified data was forwarded.

Events.BriefDescription: Counts demand instruction fetches and L1 instruction cache prefetches that were supplied by the L3 cache where a snoop was sent, the snoop hit, and modified data was forwarded.
Events.PublicDescription: Counts demand instruction fetches and L1 instruction cache prefetches that were supplied by the L3 cache where a snoop was sent, the snoop hit, and modified data was forwarded.

Events.BriefDescription: Counts L1 data cache software prefetches which include T0/T1/T2 and NTA (except PREFETCHW) that were supplied by the L3 cache where a snoop was sent, the snoop hit, but no data was forwarded.
Events.PublicDescription: Counts L1 data cache software prefetches which include T0/T1/T2 and NTA (except PREFETCHW) that were supplied by the L3 cache where a snoop was sent, the snoop hit, but no data was forwarded.

Events.BriefDescription: Counts L1 data cache software prefetches which include T0/T1/T2 and NTA (except PREFETCHW) that were supplied by the L3 cache where a snoop was sent, the snoop hit, and non-modified data was forwarded.
Events.PublicDescription: Counts L1 data cache software prefetches which include T0/T1/T2 and NTA (except PREFETCHW) that were supplied by the L3 cache where a snoop was sent, the snoop hit, and non-modified data was forwarded.

Events.BriefDescription: Counts L1 data cache software prefetches which include T0/T1/T2 and NTA (except PREFETCHW) that were supplied by the L3 cache where a snoop was sent, the snoop hit, and modified data was forwarded.
Events.PublicDescription: Counts L1 data cache software prefetches which include T0/T1/T2 and NTA (except PREFETCHW) that were supplied by the L3 cache where a snoop was sent, the snoop hit, and modified data was forwarded.

Events.BriefDescription: Counts demand data reads that were supplied by the L3 cache.
Events.PublicDescription: Counts demand data reads that were supplied by the L3 cache.

Events.BriefDescription: Counts demand reads for ownership (RFO) and software prefetches for exclusive ownership (PREFETCHW) that were supplied by the L3 cache.
Events.PublicDescription: Counts demand reads for ownership (RFO) and software prefetches for exclusive ownership (PREFETCHW) that were supplied by the L3 cache.

Events.BriefDescription: Counts the total number of mispredicted branch instructions retired for all branch types.
Events.PublicDescription: Counts the total number of mispredicted branch instructions retired.  All branch type instructions are accounted for.  Prediction of the branch target address enables the processor to begin executing instructions before the non-speculative execution path is known. The branch prediction unit (BPU) predicts the target address based on the instruction pointer (IP) of the branch and on the execution path through which execution reached this IP.    A branch misprediction occurs when the prediction is wrong, and results in discarding all instructions executed in the speculative path and re-fetching from the correct path.
